0.body: This tutorial will show you how to set up SDL2 and its subprojects on your OS and toolchain of choice.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: The aim of this tutorial is to provide SDL2 users a guide for their platform and tools. Whether you are using Makefiles on a Unix system with pkg-config, invoking your compiler straight from bash or a fully integrated IDE such as Microsoft Visual Studio on Windows or Xcode on macOS, you should be covered by this guide one way or another. Some chapters will try to be as cross-platform as possible, meaning that you should be able to take that project and run it on Windows, macOS and Linux without touching it. This is achieved by using CMake and vcpkg When possible, the other SDL2 subprojects ( Image , Mixer , Net , Sound , TTF ) will be included.
1.breadcrumbs: Introduction » What this tutorial is for
1.title: What this tutorial is for

10.body:
First start by cloning the VCPKG repository and enter the folder: git clone https://github.com/Microsoft/vcpkg.git
cd vcpkg Then run the following command to download (or compile) the executable, you can pass the -disableMetrics argument if you wish disable usage metrics: ./bootstrap-vcpkg.bat Finally, you want to modify your environment variables and add: VCPKG_ROOT C:/Path/To/VCPKG
VCPKG_DEFAULT_TRIPLET x64-windows And update your PATH by adding a new entry containing: %VCPKG_ROOT% NB: VCPKG can be on any drive, not necessarily on the C drive.
10.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Installation » Windows » VCPKG
10.title: VCPKG

11.body: The first thing you will need to install on macOS is command-line developer tools. Even if you are using Xcode tools, they will be needed to install the Homebrew package manager. To install these tools, open a terminal and run: xcode-select --install Once the command-line tools are installed, you can run this command without root privileges to install Homebrew: /bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)" Once the installation finishes, make sure to close and reopen your terminal so the environment gets set properly. Optional homebrew packages that you may be interested in: git and git-gui as Apple's versions tend to be slightly out of date. llvm for LLVM's version of Clang. gcc for the GNU C/C++ compilers. clang-format for a C/C++ code formatter.
11.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Installation » macOS » MacOS Installation
11.title: MacOS Installation

12.body:
You can install both packages at once using this command: brew install cmake ninja Add the following lines in your .zshrc (or equivalent if you use a different shell): export CMAKE_EXPORT_COMPILE_COMMANDS=ON
export CMAKE_GENERATOR=Ninja
12.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Installation » macOS » Ninja and CMake
12.title: Ninja and CMake

13.body:
First start by cloning the VCPKG repository and enter the folder: git clone https://github.com/Microsoft/vcpkg.git
cd vcpkg Then run the following command to download (or compile) the executable, you can pass the -disableMetrics argument if you wish disable usage metrics: ./bootstrap-vcpkg.sh Finally, you want to add the following lines in your ~/.zshrc: export VCPKG_ROOT=/path/to/vcpkg
export PATH="$VCPKG_ROOT:$PATH" If your device is running an M1 CPU: export VCPKG_DEFAULT_TRIPLET=arm64-osx If your device is running an Intel CPU: export VCPKG_DEFAULT_TRIPLET=x64-osx

14.body: The LLVM suite of tools will not be added to your path by default as it overlaps with Apple's version (except for clang-format), you will manually need to create the kit entry later on if you wish to use it with that setup. As the time of writing, vcpkg does not support "universal binaries", and while it is technically possible to define a custom "triplet" to create them, some dependencies of SDL2 subprojects explicitly forbid universal binaries in their CMakeLists.txt. As such only native builds will be covered.

15.body: The package names in this section will only cover Arch Linux and Ubuntu. If a package is not found, please check your own distribution package list before filing an issue.
15.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Installation » Linux » Linux Installation
15.title: Linux Installation

16.body:
Before anything, you want to ensure your system is up to date by running: sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade We will first need to install a compiler. The two main options are GCC and LLVM Clang: sudo apt install gcc
sudo apt install clang We then need to install the dependencies for VCPKG: sudo apt install cmake ninja-build git zip unzip tar curl Finally, we need some specific -dev libraries that are required to build SDL2. sudo apt install libx11-dev libxft-dev libxext-dev pkg-config You may also be interesting in installing clang-format, which provides a code formatter and clang-tidy which provides a static analyser: sudo apt install clang-format clang-tidy
16.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Installation » Linux » Ubuntu
16.title: Ubuntu

17.body:
Before anything, you want to ensure your system is up to date by running: sudo pacman -Syu We will first need to install a compiler. The two main options are GCC and LLVM Clang: sudo pacman -S gcc
sudo pacman -S clang We then need to install the dependencies for VCPKG: sudo pacman -S cmake ninja git zip unzip tar curl Finally, we need some specific libraries that are required to build SDL2. sudo pacman -S libx11 libxft libxext pkg-config
17.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Installation » Linux » Arch Linux

19.body: In this section, we will go through the extensions needed in order to use CMake and vcpkg and get syntax highlighting in C/C++.
19.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Configuring vscode » Configuring Visual Studio Code
19.title: Configuring Visual Studio Code

2.body: This guide will not cover cross-compilation in any way. It will assume that when you are targeting your own machine. Similarly, this guide assumes a fairly modern computer, capable of running Windows 10, macOS 10.15 or an up-to-date Linux distro. SDL1.2 will not be covered either, its last release was over ten years ago and has been superseded by SDL2. Lastly, this will not teach you how to use any of the libraries, some code examples will include some code from them to ensure everything worked but shall remain terse.
2.breadcrumbs: Introduction » What this tutorial is not for
2.title: What this tutorial is not for

20.body: Head over the extension menu to the left, you want the following extensions: ms-vscode.cpptools, provides C/C++ support ms-vscode.cmake-tools, provides CMake commands twxs.cmake, provide CMakeLists.txt syntax highlighting, it is planned to be integrated in cmake-tools version 1.11
20.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Configuring vscode » Extensions
20.title: Extensions

21.body:
Now that the extensions are installed, press CTRL-SHIFT-P (CMD-SHIFT-P on macOS) and type Preferences: Open Settings (JSON). You can then add the following entries: { // Previous settings here // C/C++ "C_Cpp.default.cStandard": "c17", "C_Cpp.default.cppStandard": "c++20", "C_Cpp.default.configurationProvider": "ms-vscode.cmake-tools", // CMake "cmake.configureOnOpen": false, "cmake.generator": "Ninja" // Remove this option on Windows
}
21.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Configuring vscode » Settings
21.title: Settings

22.body: For this part, you will need to open a folder with an existing CMakeLists.txt in order for the extension to show up. Start by opening an empty folder, pressing CTRL-SHIFT-P (CMD-SHIFT-P on macOS) and type CMake: Quick Start, a name for the project, and select Executable. Once the project gets created, you will start seeing new options in the blue status bar at the bottom, and will also be prompted to select a "kit" (you may need to [Scan for kits] first). If at this step no kit appears even after scanning, ensure that you have installed a compiler. We now want to add a new kit that will make use of vcpkg. Start by opening the kits' file by pressing CTRL-SHIFT-P (CMD-SHIFT-P on macOS) and typing CMake: Edit User-Local CMake Kits. Find the scanned kit using the compiler you want to use and make a copy of it. Note that if you edit a scanned kit, your modifications may be erased if you rescan kits later. Edit the kit by changing its name (for example by adding (vcpkg) at the end of it) and adding a new field: "toolchainFile": "[/path/to/vcpkg]/scripts/buildsystems/vcpkg.cmake", With the new kit saved, on the status bar, click on No Active Kit to select your new kit, then on the build right next to the kit to ensure the configuration and build works.
22.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Configuring vscode » Configuring CMake Kits
22.title: Configuring CMake Kits

23.body: There are two ways to use VCPKG, the first one includes manually using the vcpkg install command to manually install the packages, the second is to fill a project-specific vcpkg.json manifest that lists all the desired dependencies.
23.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Installing packages with VCPKG » Installing packages with VCPKG
23.title: Installing packages with VCPKG

24.body: Open a terminal and run the following command: vcpkg search sdl2 This command will list all the available SDL2 libraries and their optional features. If you want SDL2_image with libjpeg-turbo and libwebp support you would run: vcpkg install "sdl2-image[libjpeg-turbo,libwebp]" For this tutorial, we will not be using any optional features, so here is the command used: vcpkg install sdl2 sdl2-image sdl2-mixer sdl2-net sdl2-ttf NB: At the time of writing, SDL2_sound is not available on VCPKG. Finally, make the packages available user-wide with the command: vcpkg integrate install In classic mode, the packages will not be updated automatically. Make sure to go in VCPKG's folder once in a while, run git pull to get the latest changes, bootstrap a new executable, and run vcpkg update to check for package updates.

24.title: Classic mode

26.body: In this section, we will see how to tell CMake which libraries we need and how to link them.
26.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Writing a CMakeLists » Using the libraries in the build system
26.title: Using the libraries in the build system

27.body:
After VCPKG finished compiling the dependencies, it should output something similar to: The package sdl2 provides CMake targets: find_package(SDL2 CONFIG REQUIRED) target_link_libraries(main PRIVATE SDL2::SDL2 SDL2::SDL2main SDL2::SDL2-static) The package sdl2-image provides CMake targets: find_package(sdl2-image CONFIG REQUIRED) target_link_libraries(main PRIVATE SDL2::SDL2_image) The package sdl2-mixer provides CMake targets: find_package(sdl2-mixer CONFIG REQUIRED) target_link_libraries(main PRIVATE SDL2::SDL2_mixer) The package sdl2-net provides CMake targets: find_package(sdl2-net CONFIG REQUIRED) target_link_libraries(main PRIVATE SDL2::SDL2_net) The package sdl2-ttf provides CMake targets: find_package(sdl2-ttf CONFIG REQUIRED) target_link_libraries(main PRIVATE SDL2::SDL2_ttf) This roughly explains how to find and use each package. To get started, you can edit the CMakeLists.txt generated using the CMake: Quick Start command. Before the add_executable statement, you want to add the following lines: find_package(SDL2 CONFIG REQUIRED)
find_package(sdl2-image CONFIG REQUIRED)
find_package(sdl2-mixer CONFIG REQUIRED)
find_package(sdl2-net CONFIG REQUIRED)
find_package(sdl2-ttf CONFIG REQUIRED) This will tell CMake to look for all the libraries, and that they are required (configuration will fail if they are not found). After the add_executable statement, you want to add the following lines: target_link_libraries( Tutorial PRIVATE SDL2::SDL2 SDL2::SDL2main SDL2::SDL2_image SDL2::SDL2_mixer SDL2::SDL2_net SDL2::SDL2_ttf) This will tell CMake to link all the libraries to your application. Your CMakeLists.txt should look like this: cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.0.0)
project(Tutorial VERSION 0.1.0) find_package(SDL2 CONFIG REQUIRED)
find_package(sdl2-image CONFIG REQUIRED)
find_package(sdl2-mixer CONFIG REQUIRED)
find_package(sdl2-net CONFIG REQUIRED)
find_package(sdl2-ttf CONFIG REQUIRED) add_executable(Tutorial main.cpp) target_link_libraries( Tutorial PRIVATE SDL2::SDL2 SDL2::SDL2main SDL2::SDL2_image SDL2::SDL2_mixer SDL2::SDL2_net SDL2::SDL2_ttf
)

30.body: This chapter will cover Microsoft's IDE Visual Studio. Note that while Visual Studio is technically available on macOS, it does not support C/C++ , as such this chapter is only meant for Windows. Using the latest LLVM toolchain in place of the MSVC toolchain will also be covered.
30.title: Visual Studio

31.body: In this section we will cover the installation of Visual Studio and the LLVM toolchain. Please note that the LLVM toolchain depends on the Microsoft's standard library and cannot be used on its own.
31.title: Installation

32.body: You want to head to Microsoft's website and download Visual Studio 2022 Community. During the installation you want to pick the "C++ Desktop development" workflow. In the right panel, you want to make sure that the optional feature "MSVC v143 - VS 2022 C++ x64/x86 Build Tools (Latest version)" is ticked on for that workflow. Other optional features in that workflow to consider are: C++ CMake Tools For Windows for CMake support, JIT Debugger, C++ Profiling Tools, C++ Address Sanitizer, Intellicode If you want to use Microsoft's packaged LLVM toolchain, you can also tick Clang Tools for Windows, be mindful that they tend to lag behind LLVM's own release. If you want to use your own version of LLVM, you will need to go into the Individual components tab and tick the C++ Clang-cl for build tool v143 package, this should be a very light package.
32.title: Visual Studio

33.body:
You can grab the latest LLVM release using chocolatey or from their GitHub . If you use the latter, make sure to add the tools to your PATH. For Visual Studio to pick up the LLVM install, you need to create a file called Directory.Build.props containing: <Project> <PropertyGroup> <LLVMInstallDir>c:\program files\LLVM\</LLVMInstallDir> <LLVMToolsVersion>14.0.1</LLVMToolsVersion> </PropertyGroup>
</Project> You need to customize the LLVMInstallDir if you have modified it during installation, and the LLVMToolsVersion depending on the one installed. The way Visual Studio scans for this file is backward from the project folder up to the drives root. In my case, I have created a D:/dev/VS folder that holds my projects, my templates, etc. This is also where the Directory.Build.props file is placed for me, so all my projects can use the LLVM toolchain if I want to.
33.title: [OPTIONAL] LLVM

34.body: In this section, we will cover how to manually install SDL2 and its subprojects in a Visual Studio project.
34.breadcrumbs: Visual Studio » Manual dependency management » VS Project with Manual Dependency Installation
34.title: VS Project with Manual Dependency Installation

35.body:
Start by creating a new project with the template Empty Project. Give it a name and leave Place solution and project in the same directory ticked on. In your project, right click Source Files, go to Add -> New Item... and create a new C++ file called main.cpp. Paste the following code: #include <iostream> int main(int, char**) { std::cout << "Hello world\n"; return 0;
} Hit CTRL-S (save) followed by CTRL-F5 (start without a debugger) and cross your fingers to see a terminal window saying "Hello world"! We will start by preparing the settings for the project. This is when we will decide the toolchain, the warnings level and the standards. Right-click the project (not the Solution) and click on Properties. The first thing you want to do is on the top part of the window select All Configurations instead of Debug/Release and All Platforms instead of x64/Win32. In the general tab, you can choose your C and C++ standard. Do note that Visual Studio 2022 has a full support for the C++20 standard but that the C standard is a little less well supported (flags standard language feature as extensions, does not allow VLA, etc). On this same page, the Platform Toolset allows you to switch back and forth between Clang and MSVC. In the vcpkg tab, you can turn off Use Vcpkg as this will be used in a later chapter. In the C/C++ - General tab, put the Warning Level on /W4. This is a good baseline for warnings, but if you want to go further, you can turn on Treat Warnings As Errors and Enable Address Sanitizer to let your tools help you find bugs in advance. You can now click OK to save all your modifications. Lastly, press CRTL-F5 again to ensure building still works.
35.breadcrumbs: Visual Studio » Manual dependency management » Creating the project
35.title: Creating the project

36.body:
We now need to grab the development libraries for every library that we are interested into: For SDL2, head to this website and grab the file named: SDL2-devel-2.0.XX-VC.zip For SDL2_image, head to this website and grab the file named: SDL2_image-devel-2.0.X-VC.zip For SDL2_mixer, head to this website and grab the file named: SDL2_mixer-devel-2.0.X-VC.zip For SDL2_net, head to this website and grab the file named: SDL2_net-devel-2.0.X-VC.zip For SDL2_ttf, head to this website and grab the file named: SDL2_ttf-devel-2.0.X-VC.zip On Visual Studio, above the file tree, you want to click the Show All Files button. This will replace all the categories with a regular file tree. Right-click in the file tree, go to Add -> New Folder and call it External. Right click on the newly created folder and pick Open Folder in File Explorer. In this folder, you want to put the content of each archive you have downloaded. Full file tree $(ProjectDir)\External
├───SDL2-2.0.20
│ ├───docs
│ ├───include
│ └───lib
│ ├───x64
│ └───x86
├───SDL2_image-2.0.5
│ ├───include
│ └───lib
│ ├───x64
│ └───x86
├───SDL2_mixer-2.0.4
│ ├───include
│ └───lib
│ ├───x64
│ └───x86
├───SDL2_net-2.0.1
│ ├───include
│ └───lib
│ ├───x64
│ └───x86
└───SDL2_ttf-2.0.18 ├───include └───lib ├───x64 └───x86 After this step you can click again on Show All Files to disable it. You will not be able to see the External directory. Now we need to add the libraries to our project. Head back into its properties tab. In the VC++ Directories tab, you want to edit the External Include Directories. On each line, you want to add the full path to the include directory for each folder in External. The result should be: $(ProjectDir)\External\SDL2-2.0.20\include
$(ProjectDir)\External\SDL2_image-2.0.5\include
$(ProjectDir)\External\SDL2_mixer-2.0.4\include
$(ProjectDir)\External\SDL2_net-2.0.1\include
$(ProjectDir)\External\SDL2_ttf-2.0.18\include In the same tab, for each platform you want to edit the Library Directories. Similarly to the External Include Directories, on each line, you want to add the full path to the lib/x64 directory for the x64 platform and lib/x86 directory for the Win32 platform. The result should be for x64: $(ProjectDir)\External\SDL2-2.0.20\lib\x64
$(ProjectDir)\External\SDL2_image-2.0.5\lib\x64
$(ProjectDir)\External\SDL2_mixer-2.0.4\lib\x64
$(ProjectDir)\External\SDL2_net-2.0.1\lib\x64
$(ProjectDir)\External\SDL2_ttf-2.0.18\lib\x64 In the Linker/Input tab, you want to edit the Additional Dependencies. On each line, you want to add the name of the SDL2 library files. They should be: SDL2.lib
SDL2main.lib
SDL2_image.lib
SDL2_mixer.lib
SDL2_net.lib
SDL2_ttf.lib
36.breadcrumbs: Visual Studio » Manual dependency management » Adding the dependencies
36.title: Adding the dependencies

37.body:
As soon as you will try to add any SDL-related code to your application, you will notice that you are no longer able to start as you are missing some DLLs. To solve this, we need to add a bit of scripting to our Visual Studio Project. When a build is successful, this script will copy the DLLs of each subprojects and place them next to the executable. Head back into your project's properties window, down in the Build Event - Post-Build Event tab. Similar to the Library Directories, you want to add one script per platform. For x64 the script is the following: xcopy /Y /D "$(ProjectDir)External\SDL2-2.0.20\lib\x64\*.dll" "$(OutDir)"
xcopy /Y /D "$(ProjectDir)External\SDL2_image-2.0.5\lib\x64\*.dll" "$(OutDir)"
xcopy /Y /D "$(ProjectDir)External\SDL2_mixer-2.0.4\lib\x64\*.dll" "$(OutDir)"
xcopy /Y /D "$(ProjectDir)External\SDL2_net-2.0.1\lib\x64\*.dll" "$(OutDir)"
xcopy /Y /D "$(ProjectDir)External\SDL2_ttf-2.0.18\lib\x64\*.dll" "$(OutDir)" For Win32, replace the x64 in the paths with x86. The xcopy utility performs the copy, its /Y argument suppresses the confirmation prompt and its /D argument only perform the copy if the source files are newer than the destination files.

37.title: Copying the DLLs

40.body: In this section, we will cover how to install and use VCPKG to download all the libraries for a Visual Studio project.
40.breadcrumbs: Visual Studio » Using VCPKG with MSBuild » VS Project with VCPKG
40.title: VS Project with VCPKG

41.body:
We will use Chocolatey to install CMake, Ninja and git, which are needed to use VCPKG. First, head over to Chocolatey's website and follow their install instructions. Once Chocolatey is installed, open a fresh elevated prompt and run: choco install cmake git ninja Once the installation is done, navigate to the folder that will host the VCPKG installation and run: git clone https://github.com/Microsoft/vcpkg.git
cd vcpkg Then run the following command to download (or compile) the executable, you can pass the -disableMetrics argument if you wish disable usage metrics: ./bootstrap-vcpkg.bat Finally, you want to modify your environment variables and add: VCPKG_ROOT C:/Path/To/VCPKG
VCPKG_DEFAULT_TRIPLET x64-windows And update your PATH by adding a new entry containing: %VCPKG_ROOT% NB: VCPKG can be on any drive, not necessarily on the C drive.
41.breadcrumbs: Visual Studio » Using VCPKG with MSBuild » Installing VCPKG
41.title: Installing VCPKG

42.body:
With VCPKG in your path, it is pretty straight forward to install libraries and make them available to Visual Studio. As Visual Studio ships by default with both a x64 and a x86 configuration, we will install both. Start by running the following command: vcpkg search sdl2 This will list all the SDL2 packages and their available "features" in square brackets. For this tutorial, we will stick to the default set of features, but if you need more, simply append the list of features after the name. For example, "sdl2-image[libjpeg-turbo,libwebp]" will add jpeg and webp support to SDL2_image. Run the following commands to install all the packages for both x86 and x64: vcpkg instal --triplet=x86-windows sdl2 sdl2-image sdl2-mixer sdl2-net sdl2-ttf
vcpkg instal --triplet=x64-windows sdl2 sdl2-image sdl2-mixer sdl2-net sdl2-ttf Finally, let Visual Studio know about the newly installed packages with: vcpkg integrate install

42.title: Installing libraries with VCPKG

5.body: This chapter will cover a solution that should work regardless of your OS. This solution uses: Ninja as a build system. (MSBuild on Windows) CMake to generate build system files. Microsoft VCPKG to grab all the libraries. Visual Studio Code to write the code and interface with CMake It should be noted that while this solution works on Windows, macOS and Linux it is not necessarily the best solution. For example, if you are on Windows, Microsoft Visual Studio provides an overall better experience and supports all the aforementioned tools, similarly if you have access to a JetBrains CLion license, you may prefer using it instead.

50.body: This chapter will cover Apple's IDE Xcode. We will use Apple's framework format to manage the dependencies.
50.title: Xcode

51.body: In order to compile SDL_mixer, you will need to have the folder in a case-insensitive volume. This should be the default, but it is the root of errors such as: fatal error: 'ogg/ogg.h' file not found Also ensure that you check out the entire command output as these errors tend to get buried between two compile commands.
51.title: Important Note

52.body: In this section we will focus on installing Xcode and the SDL2 frameworks.
52.breadcrumbs: Xcode » Installation » Installing Xcode and dependencies
52.title: Installing Xcode and dependencies

53.body: Xcode can be installed through the App Store on any Mac device running macOS ≥ 11. If your device cannot upgrade past macOS 10.15 (Catalina), you will have to download and install Xcode manually from Apple's developer website , the last version supported is 12.4.
53.title: Xcode

54.body: The latest development library can be acquired from the official website . Once downloaded, mount the DMG file and copy the SDL2.framework folder in /Library/Frameworks/, you will be prompted for your password when doing so.
54.title: Installing Base SDL2

55.body:
At the time of writing, other than SDL_ttf, all the prebuilt frameworks do not include an arm64 build. To fix this issue, we will generate all the DMG ourselves. The next set of steps needs to be repeated for each subproject you want to add, in each command, replace [project] by the SDL_image/mixer/net/ttf: Clone the [project] repository, and enter its Xcode folder: git clone https://github.com/libsdl-org/[project].git
cd [project]/Xcode Optionally, if you wish to compile a specific version of the library, they all have release-2.0.x which you can checkout. Run the build command: xcodebuild ONLY_ACTIVE_ARCH=NO -scheme "Create DMG" -configuration Release This will compile for both arm64 and x86_64, which will allow you later on to do so yourself with your own application. You can find the resulting DMG in the [project]/Xcode/build folder, the installation is identical to SDL2.
55.title: Installing the Subprojects

56.body: You may be familiar with the "Unknown source" prompt when launching an application downloaded from outside the App Store for the first time. This also applies to frameworks, except that instead of getting a prompt it will simply not load and give you a vague error message about system policies. You can check which frameworks have this "quarantine" attribute with the command: /bin/ls -l@ /Library/Frameworks/ And you can remove the attribute on all the SDL2 frameworks with the command: sudo xattr -d com.apple.quarantine /Library/Frameworks/SDL2*
56.title: Removing the "quarantine" property

57.body: In this section, we will cover the creation of C++ projects in Xcode and linking the SDL2 dependencies.
57.breadcrumbs: Xcode » Project setup » Setting up the Xcode project
57.title: Setting up the Xcode project

58.body: Open Xcode and click "Create a new project". The only template that allows using C/C++ is Command Line Tool under the macOS tab. Select this one, give it a name and set the language to either C or C++. The other options can be set at your own discretion. Finally, select the directory you want to store the project in.
58.breadcrumbs: Xcode » Project setup » Creating a project
58.title: Creating a project

59.body: In the file tree, click on the project (top-level item) to reveal the configuration menu. On the left side of the menu, click on the project name and on build settings. Scroll down to (or search for) macOS Deployment Target, this is the minimum macOS version you want your application to run on. At the time of writing, the minimum version for base SDL is 10.6 (Snow Leopard), but while you can force your project to target the same version it may fail linking. As such, if compatibility is a concern, pick the oldest version that is supported by your version of Xcode (i.e. present in the drop-down menu). Now select your target. In the Build Phases tab, expand the Link Binary With Libraries section. This is the place you want to list all the frameworks you want to link. To add the SDL2 frameworks, click on the + symbol, at the bottom click on "Add others..." and "Add files..." and navigate to /Library/Frameworks (you can open a navigation bar with CMD+Shift+G). You can select multiple frameworks at once. Lastly, by default you will not be able to dynamically load some SDL2 libraries due to code signing. To fix this you can do either of these actions: in Signing & Capabilities, tick Disable Library Validation, or, in Build Settings, set Enable Hardened Runtime to No, or, in General, for each framework pick the option Embed & Sign (permitted by SDL2's zlib license).

7.body: In this section, we will only cover the compiler Microsoft provides with Visual Studio and the LLVM toolchain which depends on Visual Studio. If you are only running Windows and your PC is not a potato, I strongly encourage you to use Visual Studio instead of Visual Studio Code as it provides on its own all the functionalities that we are installing separately in this section and overall an overall better developer experience.

7.title: Windows Installation

8.body: You want to head to Microsoft's website and download Visual Studio 2022 Community. During the installation you want to pick the "C++ Desktop development" workflow. You want to make sure that the optional feature "MSVC v143 - VS 2022 C++ x64/x86 Build Tools (Latest version)" is ticked on.
8.breadcrumbs: CMake, VCPKG and VSCode: the silver bullet » Installation » Windows » Visual Studio
8.title: Visual Studio

9.body: In this section, we will use Chocolatey to install CMake and git. Optionally, we will also install the LLVM toolchain and Ninja. First, head over to Chocolatey's website and follow their install instructions. To install packages with chocolatey, you will need administrator privileges. You can install a sudo-like alternative using: choco install gsudo This command needs to be entered in an elevated prompt. For the rest of the commands, I will assume that this package is installed and start the commands with sudo when elevation is required. You can now install CMake and git by running: sudo choco install cmake git Finally, if you want to use the LLVM toolchain, you need to install Ninja along with it: sudo choco install llvm ninja Make sure to reboot
